      <h3>Quick Answer</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>For muscle preservation after 40, the priority order is: <strong>Whey first, Casein second, Collagen third.</strong></li>
        <li>Collagen is an incomplete protein — it lacks tryptophan and is low in leucine, the amino acid that triggers muscle protein synthesis.</li>
        <li>Collagen provides real benefits for joints, skin, and connective tissue — but those grams don't count the same as whey or casein for muscle goals.</li>
        <li>Whey's fast digestion makes it ideal post-workout and at breakfast. Casein's slow digestion makes it ideal before bed.</li>
        <li>Most men over 40 only need one supplement: whey. The rest is food.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- THE CORRECTION -->
    <h2>The Collagen Misconception You Need to Hear</h2>

    <div class="correction-box">
      <div class="correction-label">⚠ Common Misconception</div>
      <p>Collagen is often marketed for muscle recovery, which creates the impression that it's equivalent to whey or casein for muscle-building purposes. It isn't. <strong>Collagen is an incomplete protein</strong> — it lacks tryptophan entirely and contains minimal leucine, the amino acid that acts as the "on switch" for muscle protein synthesis. Without the full spectrum of essential amino acids, your body cannot complete the muscle-building process — no matter how many grams you consume. For men over 40 looking to maintain or build muscle, whey is the superior choice. Collagen should be treated as a secondary supplement for joint, skin, and connective tissue health — not a primary protein source.</p>
    </div>

    <p>This matters because men who add collagen to their morning coffee and count it toward their daily protein goal are inflating their number with grams that don't trigger muscle building. A 10g collagen scoop is not the same as 10g from Greek yogurt. Not even close, biologically speaking.</p>

