    <!-- SECTION: THE SCIENCE ON WHEY -->
    <h2>Why Whey Is the Clear Winner for Muscle After 40</h2>

    <p>The case for whey as the primary supplement for men over 40 comes down to one word: leucine. Leucine is the amino acid that directly activates the mTOR pathway — the molecular switch that initiates muscle protein synthesis. After 40, <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/">anabolic resistance</a> means your muscles need a higher leucine concentration per meal to generate the same response they'd have had at 30. Whey delivers that concentration faster and in higher amounts than any other protein supplement.</p>

    <p>A 25g scoop of whey contains approximately 2.5–3g of leucine — enough to reliably trigger MPS in most men over 40. The same weight of collagen contains roughly 0.05g of leucine. That's not a minor difference. It's the difference between triggering muscle building and not.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <p><strong>The practical implication:</strong> If you're 200 lbs and your daily target is 130g, and 20g of that is coming from collagen, you're actually operating at 110g of muscle-available protein — and that 20g isn't pulling its weight. The <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/is-100g-protein-enough-200lb-man/">100g post</a> showed exactly why every gram at or below your floor matters. Collagen grams don't count the same way.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION: CASEIN'S REAL ROLE -->
    <h2>Casein's Real Role — The Overnight Anti-Catabolic</h2>

    <p>Casein is made from the same milk protein source as whey but behaves completely differently in digestion. Where whey floods your bloodstream with amino acids quickly, casein forms a gel in your stomach and releases amino acids slowly over 6–8 hours.</p>

    <p>This makes casein nearly useless post-workout — you want fast amino acid delivery when your muscles are primed for recovery. But it makes casein uniquely valuable before bed, when you're about to enter an 8-hour fast. Research shows that a pre-sleep casein dose of 30–40g meaningfully reduces overnight muscle protein breakdown compared to going to bed without it.</p>

    <p>For most men over 40, cottage cheese is the practical casein source — one cup contains roughly 25g of slow-digesting casein protein naturally. No supplement needed. But if you're already hitting your whole-food targets and want to push overnight recovery, a casein shake before bed is the most evidence-backed use of a protein supplement beyond whey.</p>

